                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Merc. Liby. March 6. 1888.<lb/>
                Rev. Dr. Morais&#44; 546. N. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/>
                My dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>My thanks for your card<lb/> of 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> rec<hi rend="sup">d</hi>.  As you do not see what<lb/> is pubd in remote places on the question<lb/> of &#34;two kinds of wine&#34; and &#34;Passov. Wine&#44;&#34;<lb/> it must seem strange that I should<lb/> repeatedly trouble you with questions.<lb/>  I feel myself under obligation to you<lb/> for your kind replies.<lb/></p>
            <p>Men are quoting one and another<lb/> minister of your religion &#40;chiefly mins.<lb/> in England&#41; as saying with great de&#45;<lb/>cision&#95;&#95;&#34;Oh no&#33; we never use fermented<lb/> wine in the Passover observances.&#34;  As<lb/> if the very thought of using it were hor&#45;<lb/>rifying&#33;  Such quotations are constantly<lb/> going the rounds.  Such a declaration was<lb/> perseveringly attributed to Rev. S. M. Isaacs.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>The son&#44; Rev. A. S. Isaacs&#44; said that<lb/> he did not believe that his father ever<lb/> made such a statement.  And now Dr.<lb/> Gordon of Boston has obtained such a<lb/> declaration from Mr. Marcus.  These<lb/> statements are used by our pertinacious<lb/> <hi rend="underline">two&#45;wine</hi> men&#44; as showing that your<lb/> people&#44; when true to their traditions&#44;<lb/> refine to use <hi rend="underline">fermented wine</hi> whenever a<lb/> <hi rend="underline">leavened</hi> article is excluded.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have sometimes thought that<lb/> <hi rend="underline">possibly</hi> some of your people&#44; who<lb/> have always seen the raisin wine<lb/> used&#44; may have grown up with the<lb/> impression that this article is used<lb/> <hi rend="underline">for the sake of avoiding fermentation</hi>.<lb/>  For example&#58; A Bapt. min. in Virginia has<lb/> just pub<hi rend="sup">d</hi>. in a Richmond paper that he<lb/> asked a boy of your people what sort of<lb/> wine was used at Passover&#44; and the boy<lb/> replied&#45;&#45;&#34;We always use unfermented wine.&#34;<lb/>  Such things abound in distant papers.<lb/>  You will see therefore&#44; that it is quite<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>natural for us to persecute well&#45;informed<lb/> men with questions.<lb/></p>
            <p>I should like to be able to say&#44; if<lb/> it would be correct&#44; that no minister<lb/> of your religion in this country&#44; of<lb/> standing and authority&#44; has ever<lb/> instructed his congregation that im&#45;<lb/>ported Passover wine&#44; duly prepared&#44;<lb/> ought not to be used during the<lb/> Passover period <hi rend="underline">because it is fer&#45;<lb/>mented&#44; and is therefore leavened</hi>.  As<lb/> to my <hi rend="underline">other</hi> reasons for discouraging<lb/> the use of it I should have no occasion<lb/> to say anything.  But I should like<lb/> to know whether <hi rend="underline">any</hi> authorized teacher<lb/> has been known to discourage the use<lb/> of it <hi rend="underline">because it is fermented</hi> and is to<lb/> be regarded as <hi rend="underline">leavened</hi>.  If I can<lb/> say that such instruction is not<lb/> known to have been given by any<lb/> authorized minister among your<lb/> people&#44; it will be a very impressive<lb/> statement.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>Please to bear in mind that we<lb/> have to deal with ignorant and<lb/> obstinate men who are making<lb/> themselves instructors of &#34;the masses&#34;.<lb/>  They are resolved not to learn&#44; if<lb/> they can avoid it.  They degrade<lb/> and disgrace the Temp. work.<lb/></p>
            <p>Pardon&#44; therefore&#44; our reiteration.<lb/>  Thanking you for your kindness&#44;<lb/> I am&#44; with high regard&#44;<lb/> Yours&#44; S. C. Brace.<lb/> Merc. Liby. 10<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/></p>
            </body>
